There is an element of tautology in the three, purportedly disjunctive, conditions that are the threshold to the summary dismissal power conferred by the present rule. That element of tautology emerges because (i) frivolous proceedings would include those that have no reasonable prospect of success (see 
[4.15.10]
) and (ii) vexatious proceedings could not only include the same kinds of proceedings but would also include proceedings that were an abuse of process because they were brought for an improper purpose (see 
[4.15.15]
). Because of this element of overlap between the three threshold conditions, the following notes are substantially confined to the questions of abuse of process and that absence of a reasonable cause of action.

the pursuit of proceedings that have no prospect of success: see 
[14.28.5]
;

the pursuit of proceedings for collateral purposes: see 
[14.28.10]
;

the pursuit of concurrent proceedings for substantially the same causes of action: see 
[13.4.10]
;

the pursuit of proceedings that cannot be justly determined: see 
[14.28.5]
;

the pursuit of proceedings involving relitigation of matters already determined, or which should have been determined, in prior proceedings: see 
[14.28.15]–[14.28.20]
;

the pursuit of new proceedings after unremedied default in previous proceedings for substantially the same causes of action: see 
[14.28.5]
;

taking a step in proceedings for the purpose of securing a collateral or otherwise improper advantage: see Castanho v Brown & Root (UK) Ltd [1981] AC 557 at 571; [1981] 1 All ER 143Â  (filing a notice of discontinuance) and see 
[14.28.10]
;
